04816nam a22007575i 9781501725791DE-B159720190326051319.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190326s2018    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017257917 a10.7591/97815017257912doi  a(DE-B1597)515378  a(OCoLC)1091661850  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aRC451.Z55bJ33 2005 7aHIS0010402bisacsh 7aPOL0450002bisacsh 7aPSY0150002bisacsh04a362.2/1/00968912221 aJackson, Lynette, eauthor.10aSurfacing Up :bPsychiatry and Social Order in Colonial Zimbabwe, 1908-1968 /cLynette Jackson. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource :b1 chart/graph/map, 1 table, 10 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in the History of Psychiatry00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Maps and Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tColonial and Postcolonial Place-Names -- tIntroduction. Colonial and Postcolonial Politics of Mental Health in Zimbabwe -- t1. "Lobengula's Wives Lived Here": The Colonization of Space and Meaning and the Birth of the Asylum in Southern Rhodesia -- t2. Bodies in Custody: Ingutsheni Lunatic Asylum, 1908-1933 -- t3. Black Men, White "Civilization," and Routes to Ingutsheni -- t4. Women Interrupted: Traveling Women, Anxious Men, and Ascriptions of Madness -- t5. Psychiatric Modernity in Black and White, 1933-1942 -- t6. The Africans Do Not Complain: The Monologue of Reason about Madness at Ingutsheni, 1942-1968 -- tEpilogue. Civilizing Mental Health Care: A Postcolonial Moment -- tNotes -- tIndex  aFocusing on the history of the Ingutsheni Lunatic Asylum (renamed a mental hospital after 1933), situated near Bulawayo in the former Southern Rhodesia, Surfacing Up explores the social, cultural, and political history of the colony that became Zimbabwe after gaining its independence in 1980. The phrase "surfacing up" was drawn from a conversation Lynette A. Jackson had with a psychiatric nurse who used the concept to explain what brought African potential patients into the psychiatric system. Jackson uses Ingutsheni as a reference point for the struggle to "domesticate" Africa and its citizens after conquest. Drawing on the work of Frantz Fanon, Jackson maintains that the asylum in Southern Rhodesia played a significant role in maintaining the colonial social order. She supports Fanon's claim that colonial psychiatric hospitals were repositories for those of "indocile nature" or for those who failed to fit "the social background of the colonial type."Through reconstruction and reinterpretation of patient narratives, Jackson shows how patients were diagnosed, detained, and deemed recovered. She draws on psychiatric case files to analyze the changing economic, social, and environmental conditions of the colonized, the varying needs of the white settlers, and the shifting boundaries between these two communities. She seeks to extend and enrich our understanding of how a significant institution changed the way citizens and subjects experienced the colonial social order.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2019) 0aPsychiatric hospital carezZimbabwexHistoryy20th century. 0aPsychiatryxSocial aspectszZimbabwexHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial controlzZimbabwexHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Africa / South / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066750940uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501725791423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501725791.jpg  a978-3-11-066750-9  COR eBook-Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPD